 |	(Stan and Oliver), but that would just be silly.

	See ya

	Claude

@endnode

@node developers "stanley.guide/Developers"
@prev legal

	So you think you're a developer do you?

	Stanley is fairly well structured and well written, but
	it is a small program so it is quite easy to do.  Amiga E
	is the language used, mainly because of EasyGUI, a tool
	that makes creating GUIs stupidly easy (check it out, I
	kinda hid the elegance by using objects which keep the
	structure clean).

	EasyGUI defines the structure of the program.  Each gadget
	has its own action function (PROC a_#?), and some have a
	pointer (g_#?) stored so that the contents can be modified.

	ARexx is used to communicate with OctaMED.  For example,
	the add button uses the 'sa_getrangestart' command.  There
	is a patch for OctaMED ("nsm") that uses assembly routines
	instead of ARexx, but these are only useful for getting
	values and changing note data, and can't do complicated
	things.

 |	nsm is used (if available) to enter the note and command
 |	data in notify.
 |
 |	Stanley stores the destination sample in the marker for use
 |	by notify.
 |
 |	Notify uses the length of the range in timing pulses and
 |	the total length of the samples to work out the timing pulse
 |	offset of each sample.

	The important parts of the program are the list of markers
	and the current marker.  The rest of the program merely
	allows these to be modified.

 |	Well, it does a bit more than that now, but the list of markers
 |	is still central.

	Feel free to change it however you want, it does what I want
	it to do and you can change it to do what you want it to do.

@endnode

@remark END: stanley.guide
